";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:18:"Kevin D. Hendricks";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4688:"<p>Pricing and sales can be a challenge for a lot of freelancers. We just want to do the work, and we dont want to get bogged down in how much to charge or the specifics of a sales process.</p>
<p><img src="https://ithemes.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/small-sales.jpg" alt="small-sales" width="800" height="400" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-35843" /></p>
<p>But you can make a lot more money if you put some thought into those questions. Thats why we try to help freelancers with <a href="https://ithemes.com/2015/06/15/22-freelance-pricing-tips/">pricing</a>, and one area is to focus on <strong>starting with small sales</strong>.</p>
<p><a href="http://chrislema.com/subscription-site/">Chris Lema</a> offers a great explanation of this idea in his post about subscription sites:</p>
<blockquote><p>Most people dont buy your products or services from scratch.  In order to spend money with you, they have to trust you. <br />&#8211;Chris Lema</p></blockquote>
<p>That sounds obvious enough. But we lose sight of that truth when we try to make sales. It&#8217;s tempting to skip straight to the big pitch, but you neglected to give them a reason to trust you.</p>
<p>For subscription sites, Chris points out that the initial subscription price is a big ask. Instead of jumping straight to a large, recurring payment, he recommends building trust with multiple, smaller purchases.</p>
<blockquote><p>Prime the pump by selling small products before ever making the pitch for something larger like a subscription site.<br />&#8211;Chris Lema</p></blockquote>
<p>Its an insight that goes well beyond subscription sites and applies to your freelance services.</p>
<h2 style="margin-top: 40px;">Start With Small Projects</h2>
<p>You need to build trust with clients before trying to make a big sale. Sure, you might be able to land some big sales with new clients, but those salesand the ultimate projectwould be a lot easier if you built trust with small sales first.</p>
<p><strong>You could offer small projects or services as a first step.</strong> Rather than pitching a giant website overhaul, offer to fix a few outdated plugins or tweak the funky CSS issue in their sidebar.</p>
<p><strong>Let clients experience your professionalism and skill on low-risk, small sales, and theyll be more likely to trust you with big projects.</strong></p>
<p>You just need to create opportunities for small sales.</p>
<h2 style="margin-top: 40px;">The Free Step</h2>
<p>It might not even be small sales youre offering, but small something. Maybe you have a blog where clients can get a sense of your ideas and your business savvy. Maybe you have a podcast where clients can get to know you and feel comfortable with who you are. Maybe you have an email newsletter where you can demonstrate your expertise.</p>
<p>Any of those could be the initial step that helps you build trust for a later sale. <strong>Free can work as long as youre offering real value and not just something that falls short.</strong></p>
<p>You could also move from free to small sales to larger sales. Build trust each step of the way.</p>
<h2 style="margin-top: 40px;">Examples of Small Sales</h2>
<p>Chris Lema does this with his coaching. He doesnt start by pitching his coaching, he starts with small sales such as <a href="http://chrislema.com/product/">ebooks</a> and <a href="https://clarity.fm/chrislema/">Clarity calls</a>. After getting value there, clients beg for more and he offers coaching.</p>
<p>A subscription site could do the same thing by offering ebooks or a podcast as a free or low-cost introduction to the monthly subscription site.</p>
<p>We see this all the time with software as a service offering. Theres a free or low-cost version that gets people in the door and lets them try out the service. You could do the same thing with products such as plugins or themes. (We offer a <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/better-wp-security/">free</a> version of <a href="https://ithemes.com/security/">iThemes Security Pro</a> as an introduction to the paid versions. Likewise <a href="https://ithemes.com/sync/">Sync</a> has a free level and then multiple paid offerings.)</p>
<h4 style="text-align: center; margin-top: 40px;">The important thing to remember is to offer something of value at every level, so youre building trust and laying the foundation for a future sale.</h4>
