<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://ithemes.com/2016/03/14/prequalify-clients-to-save-time-sanity/">Prequalify Clients to Save Time &amp; Sanity</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://ithemes.com">iThemes</a>.</p>
";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:18:"Kevin D. Hendricks";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8506:"<p>The life of a freelancer is busy. You need to prequalify prospects so you can save time and work more efficiently.</p>
<p><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-35759" style="margin-bottom: 40px;" src="https://ithemes.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/prequalify-clients.jpg" alt="prequalify clients" width="800" height="400" /></p>
<p>Bringing in new clients and getting more work is a good thing, but if you find yourself talking to too many prospects who dont turn into paying clients, then you might need to do more to prequalify your prospects.</p>
<p>Not every client is worth pursuing.</p>
<p><strong>Minimize the time you spend talking to clients who arent a good fit.</strong> Nobody wants to be rude, but its wasted time. The faster you can sort out which inquiries are legit and which wont work out, the more money you can make. Because talking to prospects all day doesnt pay the billsdoing the work for paying clients does.</p>
<p><strong>You prequalify your prospects to identify the clients with the most potential.</strong> Focus your time on those clients and ignore the rest (OK, maybe not ignore, but you want to turn them away, nicely).</p>
<blockquote><p>You want clients who understand and appreciate the value you bring to them and who are willing to invest in that value. &#8211;<a href="http://freelance.camp/charging-what-youre-worth/">James Dalman</a></p></blockquote>
<h2 style="margin-top: 60px;">8 Tips for Prequalifying Clients</h2>
<p>We&#8217;ve got some tips to help you prequalify your freelance clients:</p>
<h3 style="margin-top: 40px;">1. Use Your Marketing Funnel</h3>
<p>You should have a <a href="https://ithemes.com/2015/11/16/marketing-funnel-how-to-stay-busy-as-a-freelancer/">marketing funnel</a> that helps you bring in potential clients and moves them toward closing a deal. While we normally talk about that funnel as a way to bring in more clients,<strong> it should also work like a sieve, filtering out clients who dont fit.</strong></p>
<p>As you talk about your business and market yourself, you should be giving clients clues about the type of work you do, the kind of company you are and who you enjoy working with. <strong>This messaging will start doing some of the prequalifying for you.</strong></p>
<h3 style="margin-top: 40px;">2. Emphasize Your Niche</h3>
<p>As a freelancer, you should be known for a specific <a href="https://ithemes.com/2015/12/11/freelance-niche-be-known-for-something/">niche</a> or skill. Not only does this make you stand out, but its another way to prequalify clients. <strong>When youre clear about what kind of work you do (and what you dont do) its easier for clients to make a decision.</strong></p>
<h3 style="margin-top: 40px;">3. Prequalify With Your Website</h3>
<p>Your website is likely doing much of your marketing work. Likewise it should be doing a lot of your prequalifying. The way you describe yourself and the work you do should begin to filter out clients who dont fit.</p>
<p>Good website copy that explains what you do and the benefits you offer clients will help them prequalify themselves. <strong>Your personality should be reflected on your site and turn away clients who might clash (while also attracting the clients you want).</strong></p>
<blockquote><p>If you want to attract clients who are a good fit, the best way to do that is by being yourself. &#8211;<a href="http://www.carriedils.com/pitch-me-use-your-website-to-sell-your-freelance-wordpress-development-services/">Carrie Dils</a></p></blockquote>
<p>Describing your ideal project is another great way to explain what you do and help clients prequalify themselves. Testimonials and case studies will also give clients clues. If theyre a nonprofit and you do all corporate work, most clients will realize youre probably not the right fit.</p>
<h3 style="margin-top: 40px;">4. Prequalify With Email</h3>
<p>While the prequalifying starts on your website, it doesnt end there. You shouldnt talk with everyone who contacts you through your site. You need to do more filtering and thats where a focused email can help.</p>
<p><strong>You should have a good process that takes potential clients from website contact form to email to a phone call or client meeting.</strong> Use email to ask some important questions and do some thorough filtering.</p>
<p>Rebecca Gill talks about prequalifying clients in this <a href="https://ithemes.com/2016/01/27/managing-expectations-project-scoping-contracts/">project scoping webinar</a>. She has multiple standard emails to send to prospective clients depending on their exact situation.</p>
<blockquote><p>Moving to this standard email and requiring my questions to be answered before I get on the phone has meant that I close about 70% of the people I talk to on the phone instead of the 10-15% I had previously. &#8211;<a href="http://curtismchale.ca/2015/12/01/starting-your-process-right-vetting-clients/">Curtis McHale </a></p></blockquote>
<p>As you prequalify clients with email, youre not only looking at their specific answers to see if their needs match your skills, but <strong>youre also looking for red flags</strong>. Are they giving one-word answers and not really engaging? Do they take weeks on end to get back to you? Probably not someone you want to work with.</p>
<p>Here are some <a href="http://danielmall.com/articles/prequalifying-clients/">specific questions</a> you can ask via email to prequalify clients.</p>
<h3 style="margin-top: 40px;">5. Be Honest About Price</h3>
<p>You probably dont want to lock yourself into a specific price right away, but it can help to give potential clients a range or a vague understanding of what this is going to cost.</p>
<p>Even if you charge by the project, mentioning your hourly rate can be a good filter. If they choke when they hear your rate, its probably not a good fit.</p>
<p>Another approach is to ask what their budget is. Some clients will be reluctant to share numbers, but you need to know if they can even afford your services.</p>
<p><strong>You want to find out if the client is in the right ballpark in terms of price.</strong> If your average site is $5,000, that can be a way to filter out the clients who want a $500 site.</p>
<h3 style="margin-top: 40px;">6. Talk to the Right People</h3>
<p>Dont waste time talking to someone who cant make the decision. Sure, the low-level manager who knows websites loves your work and wants to hire you. <strong>But you need to talk to the person with the power to make the decision.</strong> Thats who you need to convince, and you need to talk directly to them to learn what the real challenges are for the project.</p>
<h3 style="margin-top: 40px;">7. Say No But Give Options</h3>
<p>Not every client is going to be a good fit. Thats OK. <strong>Be willing to say no.</strong> The client might be too cheap for your tastes or they want something you dont really offer. Maybe theres a personality clash and you cant imagine having to work with this person.</p>
<p>But the whole point of prequalifying prospects is that youre filtering out clients who arent a good fit. <strong>Youre supposed to be saying no.</strong> So its OK to do it.</p>
<p>Just be sure to give them something. Recommend someone else who might be a better fit. Theyll be grateful, theyll better understand what you do, and they might in turn recommend you to another client whos a better fit.</p>
<h3 style="margin-top: 40px;">8. Listen to Your Gut</h3>
<p><strong>So how do you feel about a project?</strong> Are you eager to dive in or, in the words of every Star Wars character, do you have a bad feeling about this? If youre seeing red flags or something feels off, pay attention to that feeling.</p>
<p>If youre not excited about a project, then why do it?</p>
<h2 style="margin-top: 40px;">Get to Work</h2>
<p><strong>Prequalify your clients so you can save time and make the most of your day.</strong> Putting a little effort into creating systems and processes will pay off in saved time and fewer headaches. </p>
